                    The Secret Life of Business Class Seats                
Jad Mouawad visits B/E Aerospace to see the technology behind business class seats.
Kassie Bracken

















                    In Bantam, Rebuilding From Scratch                
WHEN B/E Aerospace announced last October that it would close its factory in Bantam, about 350 people knew they would soon be looking for new jobs. The company, which shut down Feb. 28, made airplane seats and was the biggest employer in Litchfield County. Months later, conversations in and around Bantam still quickly turn to B/E, with many people wondering how the former employees are faring.










COMPANY NEWS

                    B/E AEROSPACE PLANS TO BUY AIRCRAFT MODULAR PRODUCTS                
B/E Aerospace Inc. said yesterday that it planned to buy the closely held Aircraft Modular Products for $118 million in cash. Aircraft Modular Products has a 60 percent share of the market for new business jet interiors and more than 10,000 installed interiors that may need replacement parts. B/E Aerospace, based in Wellington, Fla., is the world's largest maker of aircraft cabin seats, kitchens, storage areas and bathrooms. With Aircraft Modular, which is based in Miami, B/E Aerospace would also be the largest manufacturer and supplier of interiors for the business jet industry. Shares of B/E Aerospace rose 56.25 cents yesterday, to $34.1875.










COMPANY NEWS

                    BE AEROSPACE SHARES DROP ON BRITISH AIRWAYS DECISION                
The stock of BE Aerospace Inc. skidded 17 percent yesterday after British Airways P.L.C. said it would not buy the company's upscale in-flight video system. Despite reporting record earnings in the second quarter, shares of BE Aerospace dropped $6.50, to $34.25, in Nasdaq trading. British Airways told BE Aerospace, which is based in Wellington, Fla., that it would not consider buying its MDDS multimedia entertainment system, which allows passengers to choose audio and video selections individually, but would instead test the company's 12-channel video system through Dec. 15.











                    COMPANY BRIEFS                
BE AEROSPACE CORP., Wellington, Fla., said it had agreed to buy Philips Airvision, a unit of Philips Electronics for $12 million in cash. HAWKEYE BANCORPORATION, Des Moines, said it would buy Centre Pointe Leasing Co. for an undisclosed amount.
















